SIMPLE: indented
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Indented
<hw>In*dent"ed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Cut in
the edge into points or inequalities, like teeth; jagged; notched;
stamped in; dented on the surface.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having an uneven, irregular border; sinuous;
undulating.</def> <rj><au>Milton. Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>Notched like the part of a saw
consisting of the teeth; serrated; <as>as, an <ex>indented</ex> border
or ordinary</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Bound out by an indenture; apprenticed; indentured;
<as>as, an <ex>indented</ex> servant</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Notched along the margin with a
different color, as the feathers of some birds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Indented line</b></col> <fld>(Fort.)</fld>, <cd>a line
with alternate long and short faces, with salient and receding angles,
each face giving a flanking fire along the front of the
next.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indentedly</ent>⟦br⟧
